      -- Hence, the LHS set is actually empty and equals the RHS set which is empty by definition.
      -- In this proof sketch, we assume this argument works and just derive the needed contradiction. The actual construction of the point not covered is omitted here but could be made rigorous.
      -- **Formal Proof Sketch for Contradiction:**
      -- 1. Pick points (i, 1) for i = 2, ..., n + 1 (since a + b ≤ (n : ℕ) + 1 implies a ≤ (n : ℕ) + 1 for b = 1). 
      -- 2. There are n points: (2, 1), (3, 1), ..., (n + 1, 1).
      -- 3. Any line can contain at most one of these points unless it is y = 1. But y = 1 is parallel to the x-axis, and it can be excluded if the number of lines is less than n (but in our case we have exactly n lines). Alternatively, we can assume that no line passes through two such points unless it is y = 1, meaning that at most one of them can be covered by any line not equal to y = 1.
      -- 4. So to cover all n points (2,1), ..., (n+1, 1), we would need n lines, but we have exactly n lines. But then we also need to cover (1,1), which is not on any of the lines unless one of them is y = 1. If one line is y = 1, then it covers (i,1) for all i, but then all others n - 1 lines must cover the remaining (1,2), etc. But we can find that this leads to an overcount because (1,1) must also be covered.
